MYC degradation, but this molecule is now substantially more durable in its

234
00:13:16.364 --> 00:13:20.184
action. We see now MYC degradation out to 24 hours as opposed to recovery by

235
00:13:20.264 --> 00:13:20.584
six.

236
00:13:21.424 --> 00:13:25.224
And by chemoproteomic approaches, this molecule still engages MYC, but with

237
00:13:25.284 --> 00:13:28.914
far fewer off-targets now. Now, there are still a number of off-targets that still

238
00:13:28.983 --> 00:13:32.864
have to be dialed out, but far fewer than the original hit molecule that I

239
00:13:32.904 --> 00:13:36.764
showed you. And by global proteomics on the right, this molecule is exceptionally

240
00:13:36.804 --> 00:13:40.664
selective at degrading MYC in cells with very few other proteins

241
00:13:40.924 --> 00:13:44.564
changing. And so this has given us confidence that intrinsically

242
00:13:44.604 --> 00:13:48.344
disordered regions, at least some of them, can actually be tackled with covalent

243
00:13:48.364 --> 00:13:49.084
small molecules,

244
00:13:50.314 --> 00:13:53.184
these IDR regions within transcription factors like MYC.

245
00:13:53.244 --> 00:13:56.874
And subsequently, we've also been able to develop these covalent destabilizing

246
00:13:56.904 --> 00:13:58.924
degraders. For example, against beta-catenin.

247
00:13:59.404 --> 00:14:02.724
In collaboration with Amgen, we were able to develop one against AR and ARV7.

248
00:14:02.904 --> 00:14:06.544
And in collaboration with Octant, we were able to develop a covalent

249
00:14:06.564 --> 00:14:10.544
destabilizing degrader against the inflammatory transcription factors IRF5 and

250
00:14:10.604 --> 00:14:11.194
IRF8.

251
00:14:13.844 --> 00:14:17.184
But I alluded earlier again to the fact that transcription factors are really hard

252
00:14:17.224 --> 00:14:20.824
to go after, not just because they're difficult to ligand, but also because they

253
00:14:20.864 --> 00:14:24.544
have very fast turnover rate. So degradation may not even be the

254
00:14:24.644 --> 00:14:28.194
best way to be able to disrupt transcription factors, because the cell will just

255
00:14:28.244 --> 00:14:30.544
resynthesize the transcription factor quite rapidly.

256
00:14:31.164 --> 00:14:35.124
Now, there are certainly ways to do this with a lot of the efforts that have gone

257
00:14:35.164 --> 00:14:38.524
into epigenetic drug discovery. But many of those

258
00:14:38.884 --> 00:14:42.104
epigenetic inhibitors, like dual EP300/CBP inhibitors or

259
00:14:42.164 --> 00:14:45.984
SMARCA2/SMARCA4 inhibitors, because they manipulate the transcription of many

260
00:14:46.064 --> 00:14:49.124
genes, their therapeutic window has been relatively limited.

261
00:14:52.244 --> 00:14:55.504
So what you'd like to be able to do is do this in a loci-specific manner.

262
00:14:56.004 --> 00:14:59.044
And there are ways to do this, for example, with epigenome editing, where you can

263
00:14:59.104 --> 00:15:02.524
take a dCas9 with a guide RNA and fuse it to a DNA

264
00:15:02.584 --> 00:15:06.264
methyltransferase to methylate specific genomic loci in a

265
00:15:06.304 --> 00:15:10.244
site-specific manner. But these are 500 kilodalton protein complexes,

266
00:15:10.284 --> 00:15:13.044
and are going to have major problems with systemic delivery.

267
00:15:13.564 --> 00:15:16.324
And so can we do this with a completely small molecule-based approach?

268
00:15:16.364 --> 00:15:20.344
And so that's what we've tried to do here with this transcriptional repression via

269
00:15:20.354 --> 00:15:24.104
active chemical epigenetic reprogramming, or what we call TRACERS, where we've been

270
00:15:24.164 --> 00:15:28.113
able to develop recruiters against transcriptional repression machinery that brings

271
00:15:28.113 --> 00:15:31.994
in things like histone deacetylases as part of the nucleosome remodeling complex,

272
00:15:32.344 --> 00:15:36.104
and then link those recruiters to transcription factor targeting ligands to now

273
00:15:36.144 --> 00:15:39.743
recruit transcriptional repression complexes to specific genetic loci

274
00:15:40.124 --> 00:15:44.104
to epigenetically silence and shut down transcriptional programming in

275
00:15:44.144 --> 00:15:47.804
a loci-specific manner, and also with a completely, fully small molecule-based

276
00:15:47.884 --> 00:15:48.264
approach.

277
00:15:49.324 --> 00:15:52.884
And so out of patent literature, we were able to identify this

278
00:15:52.944 --> 00:15:56.344
molecule that binds and inhibits this methyl binding protein,

279
00:15:56.484 --> 00:16:00.384
MBD2. MBD2 usually

280
00:16:00.404 --> 00:16:04.164
binds to CpG methylated oligo islands, DNA

281
00:16:04.224 --> 00:16:08.164
islands, to bring in the nucleosome remodeling complex to deacetylate and shut

282
00:16:08.204 --> 00:16:11.264
down transcription at specific genetic components.

283
00:16:11.364 --> 00:16:14.844
And we wanted to further validate this molecule, and so we made a photoaffinity

284
00:16:15.464 --> 00:16:18.304
alkyne functionalized probe version out of this, and we could show that compared to

285
00:16:18.324 --> 00:16:21.864
the negative control, we can enrich out MBD2 out of cells.

286
00:16:21.904 --> 00:16:24.324
And so it showed nice cellular target engagement.

287
00:16:24.904 --> 00:16:28.704
We also, in collaboration with Novartis, were able to reconstitute the

288
00:16:28.744 --> 00:16:30.204
nucleosome remodeling complex.

289
00:16:31.144 --> 00:16:34.744
And while this molecule doesn't seem to bind to the individual components of

290
00:16:34.824 --> 00:16:38.664
MBD2 or HDAC1 alone, when you put them together assembled in a

291
00:16:38.724 --> 00:16:41.024
complex, you actually see now robust binding.

292
00:16:41.054 --> 00:16:44.724
And so it seems like this molecule binds really only in the context of the full

293
00:16:45.104 --> 00:16:48.564
complex, which certainly exists in cells, and so that's why we also capture it in

294
00:16:48.604 --> 00:16:52.440
cells.So with that invalidation in hand, we then went after proof of

295
00:16:52.540 --> 00:16:56.200
concept of this approach, initially going after the estrogen receptor just because

296
00:16:56.260 --> 00:16:59.040
it's such a well-validated target in breast cancer and there's a lot of

297
00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:00.560
pharmacology associated with it.

298
00:17:01.180 --> 00:17:05.020
We took this estrone derivative, which is an ER agonist, as our ER targeting

299
00:17:05.080 --> 00:17:08.641
ligand. And on the top here, while the MBD2 inhibitor or the

300
00:17:08.720 --> 00:17:12.641
estrone ligand alone either stimulates or doesn't do anything to ER transcription

301
00:17:12.661 --> 00:17:16.131
activity in breast cancer cells, when you now link these together in the

302
00:17:16.161 --> 00:17:19.990
heterobifunctional molecule, we see now an over 90% suppression of

303
00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:23.940
ER transcription activity in cells already at a high nanomolar concentration.

304
00:17:24.460 --> 00:17:27.040
And this molecule turns out to be incredibly durable.

305
00:17:27.100 --> 00:17:30.620
You can treat cells for just a few hours, wash out the compound, and transcription

306
00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:33.240
stays inhibited for days afterwards.

307
00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:35.720
And so it's an incredibly durable response.

308
00:17:36.480 --> 00:17:39.630
To show you this is on-target activity, we could show a rescue of the

309
00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:43.620
transcriptional inhibition with either excess of the MBD2 inhibitor or

310
00:17:44.060 --> 00:17:44.200
with

311
00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:48.420
competition

312
00:17:48.440 --> 00:17:50.370
with a histone deacetylase inhibitor.

313
00:17:51.070 --> 00:17:55.040
Indicating that, again, we're not sequestering ER away from its native

314
00:17:55.080 --> 00:17:58.980
loci or disrupting ER protein complexes to inhibit ER transcription.

315
00:17:59.040 --> 00:18:02.620
It actually requires the activity of HDAC being brought in through the

316
00:18:02.660 --> 00:18:05.700
nucleosome remodeling complex to have that inhibitory activity.

317
00:18:06.200 --> 00:18:07.100
And also to show

318
00:18:08.440 --> 00:18:12.040
on-target mechanism of action, MBD2 knockdown also rescues this

319
00:18:12.080 --> 00:18:14.460
transcriptional inhibitory activity that we see.

320
00:18:15.060 --> 00:18:18.760
When we do RNA-seq, again, we're not just globally screwing up transcription, but

321
00:18:18.780 --> 00:18:20.040
we're quite selectively

322
00:18:20.960 --> 00:18:22.710
down-regulating ER target genes.

323
00:18:23.020 --> 00:18:26.500
So we do a pathway analysis, ER pathways are the top pathways that are

324
00:18:26.540 --> 00:18:30.060
disrupted. And when you knock down MBD2, you basically get a

325
00:18:30.120 --> 00:18:31.700
transcriptionally silent signature.

326
00:18:31.760 --> 00:18:34.300
So all the kind of global transcriptomic

327
00:18:36.180 --> 00:18:39.140
profiles that we observe are really all driven through MBD2.

328
00:18:40.140 --> 00:18:43.820
We've also done ATAC-seq to look at general chromatin accessibility to make sure

329
00:18:43.840 --> 00:18:46.580
that we're not screwing up global chromatin accessibility.

330
00:18:47.060 --> 00:18:49.940
And quite gratifyingly, we see that we're quite

331
00:18:50.060 --> 00:18:53.600
selectively blunting ER loci

332
00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:56.780
chromatin accessibility. Again, showing the selectivity of this molecule

333
00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:58.640
manipulating ER target genes.

334
00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:03.880
And so, that was a nice proof of concept, but there are already quite robust

335
00:19:03.980 --> 00:19:07.500
ways to antagonize ER with things like fulvestrant and

336
00:19:08.040 --> 00:19:11.900
other ER antagonists. So we wanted to go after more of a clinically

337
00:19:11.980 --> 00:19:15.650
unmet need proof of concept, such as, for example, the truncation variant of the

338
00:19:15.760 --> 00:19:19.500
androgen receptor, AR-V7, that drives androgen-independent prostate cancer

339
00:19:19.540 --> 00:19:23.300
cells. And the reason why this is really undruggable is that AR-V7 is

340
00:19:23.340 --> 00:19:27.240
basically missing the entire steroid-binding domain or ligand-binding domain that

341
00:19:27.680 --> 00:19:29.560
AR antagonists like enzalutamide bind to.

342
00:19:29.580 --> 00:19:32.780
And all that's left is a highly intrinsically disordered and now permanently

343
00:19:32.900 --> 00:19:35.180
activated DNA binding and N-terminal domain.

344
00:19:36.380 --> 00:19:40.260
But all of these prostate cancer cells still express full-length AR

345
00:19:40.340 --> 00:19:43.640
alongside AR-V7. And so if you, for example, take

346
00:19:44.080 --> 00:19:47.990
enzalutamide or, in this case, a selective androgen receptor modulator, in those

347
00:19:48.040 --> 00:19:51.800
cells, you only get about a partial 40% inhibition of AR transcription

348
00:19:51.900 --> 00:19:55.660
activity because the other 50% to 60% is driven by AR-V7.

349
00:19:55.700 --> 00:19:59.620
But AR and AR-V7 are still binding to the same genetic loci.

350
00:20:00.080 --> 00:20:03.860
So if you epigenetically shut down AR loci, you'll by default also shut down

351
00:20:03.960 --> 00:20:07.800
AR-V7 loci as well. And so consistent with that now, when we take the

352
00:20:07.840 --> 00:20:11.580
selective androgen receptor modulator on the left and then link it to the MBD2

353
00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:12.380
recruiter on the right,

354
00:20:13.400 --> 00:20:17.350
you get over a 90% suppression of AR transcription activity in

355
00:20:17.460 --> 00:20:21.420
22RV1 androgen-independent prostate cancer cells that express both

356
00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:25.020
AR and AR-V7. And you can rescue that again with an HDAC

357
00:20:25.060 --> 00:20:27.160
inhibitor or with MBD2 knockdown.

358
00:20:27.220 --> 00:20:31.080
And when you do RNA-seq, you see a global suppression of all the AR target genes,

359
00:20:31.300 --> 00:20:35.150
much, much more so than you would observe with AR antagonists in these cells,

360
00:20:35.180 --> 00:20:38.680
like enzalutamide, which again, only partially inhibits function.

361
00:20:39.080 --> 00:20:42.580
And so we're quite excited about this approach to be able to now

362
00:20:42.860 --> 00:20:46.620
epigenetically and loci specifically, and in a fully small molecule-based approach,

363
00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:50.560
shut down specific transcriptional programming in a much more durable

364
00:20:50.640 --> 00:20:54.320
manner than you might even get with a degrader type approach.

365
00:20:55.900 --> 00:20:58.760
In the last few minutes, I also want to extend this to molecular glues.

366
00:20:58.960 --> 00:21:02.680
Because the approach that I just showed you was with a heterobifunctional molecule,

367
00:21:02.740 --> 00:21:06.680
which again, is larger molecular weight, has a heavier lift on med chem to make

368
00:21:06.720 --> 00:21:10.440
it more drug-like. How do you do this with non-degradative molecular

369
00:21:10.520 --> 00:21:14.020
glues? How do you rationally discover these types of things, especially as it

370
00:21:14.040 --> 00:21:17.429
relates to transcription? And in my classrooms, I always give this

371
00:21:17.480 --> 00:21:21.440
example of, for example, rapamycin that Jerry Crabtree and Stu

372
00:21:21.520 --> 00:21:25.100
Schreiber discovered as a molecular glue between FKBP12 and mTOR.

373
00:21:26.100 --> 00:21:29.760
And then 30 years later now, we have amazing programs from Revolution Medicines

374
00:21:30.140 --> 00:21:34.060
developing pan-RAS inhibitors that acts through molecular glue

375
00:21:34.100 --> 00:21:37.640
interactions with cyclophilin. But no medicinal chemistry biologist would have

376
00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:41.320
thought, "I'm going to drug RAS by gluing it to this random protein cyclophilin,"

377
00:21:41.380 --> 00:21:44.620
without the original discoveries from Stu Schreiber and Jerry Crabtree.

378
00:21:45.580 --> 00:21:49.560
And so how do you do this against other targets while still allowing

379
00:21:49.600 --> 00:21:53.000
for optimistic discoveries on the effector

380
00:21:53.040 --> 00:21:56.908
side?And so we've taken the exact same strategies we've taken

381
00:21:56.928 --> 00:22:00.448
for rational molecular glue degrader design, where we start with a protein

382
00:22:00.528 --> 00:22:04.208
targeting ligand and then elaborate a variety of kind of electrophilic fragments

383
00:22:04.348 --> 00:22:07.768
off of it to look, in this case now, not for degradation.

384
00:22:08.128 --> 00:22:11.308
In fact, we specifically exclude degradation as an outcome, but rather for

385
00:22:11.368 --> 00:22:13.408
neomorphic transcriptional activity downstream.

386
00:22:14.028 --> 00:22:16.788
And so to show proof of concept of this in our first example,

387
00:22:17.628 --> 00:22:21.208
we were really inspired by work coming out of Gerry Crabtree and Nathaniel Gray's

388
00:22:21.248 --> 00:22:25.048
lab on these transcriptional epigenetic chemical inducers of

389
00:22:25.068 --> 00:22:28.928
proximity, or TSIPs, where they were able to take a BRD4

390
00:22:28.968 --> 00:22:32.848
inhibitor, JQ1, that brings a transcriptional activation BAF complex and link

391
00:22:32.968 --> 00:22:36.788
it to a BCL6 inhibitor, where BCL6

392
00:22:37.048 --> 00:22:38.428
is a transcriptional repressor.

393
00:22:39.668 --> 00:22:43.458
And thereby, by bringing an activator to a transcriptional repressor, you

394
00:22:43.608 --> 00:22:47.528
de-repressed BCL6 transcription, and that really potently killed cancer cells.

395
00:22:48.068 --> 00:22:51.268
But in their paper, another thing that was really intriguing to me was they saw a

396
00:22:51.428 --> 00:22:55.408
global suppression of MYC in addition to de-repression of BCL6,

397
00:22:55.468 --> 00:22:59.328
indicating maybe this isn't just a simple on switch, but maybe it's actually

398
00:22:59.388 --> 00:23:03.168
rewiring transcription. And so we wanted to further delve deeper

399
00:23:03.188 --> 00:23:06.848
into that. And so we took a BCL6 inhibitor like they did,

400
00:23:07.268 --> 00:23:10.768
and then instead of linking it in the hetero-bifunctional format, we just

401
00:23:10.808 --> 00:23:14.628
elaborated a variety of electrophilic handles off of it without a linker.

402
00:23:15.188 --> 00:23:18.628
And we specifically looked now for MYC downregulation more than what the

403
00:23:18.648 --> 00:23:21.028
BCL6 inhibitor or the degrader could do alone.

404
00:23:21.068 --> 00:23:25.048
And we were able to identify this molecule, this ZD186 molecule

405
00:23:25.058 --> 00:23:29.028
that you see the BCL6 inhibitor in green and then the covalent

406
00:23:29.128 --> 00:23:32.968
handle in blue that's presumably covalently attaching to something and gluing it

407
00:23:33.028 --> 00:23:36.828
to BCL6. And by Western blotting, you could see that not only

408
00:23:36.868 --> 00:23:40.668
BCL6 target genes like P21 are being de-repressed, but you also

409
00:23:40.728 --> 00:23:44.388
see that downregulation of MYC. When you do a time course, you actually see that

410
00:23:44.428 --> 00:23:47.928
MYC downregulation happens faster than P21 upregulation.

411
00:23:48.008 --> 00:23:50.488
So these things are clearly kind of uncoupled, right?

412
00:23:50.548 --> 00:23:53.968
And the MYC downregulation is actually happening first.

413
00:23:54.588 --> 00:23:57.938
So we wanted to see what we were actually gluing to BCL6, and so we did a simple

414
00:23:57.948 --> 00:24:01.588
BCL6 pull-down in the presence of our molecular glue, and we pulled out

415
00:24:01.608 --> 00:24:05.298
BRD9, which biologically may not have been that interesting because

416
00:24:06.028 --> 00:24:09.248
Nathaniel Gray was able to show with BRD4 that you could do this.

417
00:24:09.288 --> 00:24:12.708
BRD9 is another bromodomain that brings a non-canonical

418
00:24:13.128 --> 00:24:16.948
BAF activation complex. And so we were able to show that ternary

419
00:24:17.008 --> 00:24:20.888
complex formation. We were also able to show that this reacts with an allosteric

420
00:24:20.908 --> 00:24:24.597
cysteine 288 on BRD9. And this is, in fact, very

421
00:24:25.608 --> 00:24:27.048
much the mechanism of this molecule.

422
00:24:27.128 --> 00:24:30.568
You can show that the MYC downregulation and the P21

423
00:24:30.608 --> 00:24:34.528
upregulation can be rescued with a BRD9 seven inhibitor, but not with a negative

424
00:24:34.548 --> 00:24:38.228
control inhibitor. And if you knock out BRD9, you also get full

425
00:24:38.248 --> 00:24:41.528
rescue of the MYC downregulation and P21 upregulation.

426
00:24:41.668 --> 00:24:45.097
And by RNA-seq, once again, we see a global de-repression of

427
00:24:45.128 --> 00:24:48.758
BCL6 target genes, but we also see a global suppression of

428
00:24:48.928 --> 00:24:52.668
MYC genes as well. And so what we think is happening in this case

429
00:24:52.728 --> 00:24:56.638
is on the left here, not only are we recruiting a transcriptional activation

430
00:24:56.708 --> 00:25:00.228
complex by recruiting BRD9 to BCL6 loci to

431
00:25:00.248 --> 00:25:03.868
de-repress BCL6. But BCL6 is a transcriptional repressor in

432
00:25:03.928 --> 00:25:07.628
itself that can recruit things like the NCOR or SMART transcriptional repressing

433
00:25:07.688 --> 00:25:10.668
complexes. And so we think that we're also recruiting those transcriptional

434
00:25:10.688 --> 00:25:14.488
repression complexes, the oncogenic BRD9 loci, to shut down MYC

435
00:25:14.508 --> 00:25:17.928
transcription as well. And we're now, through pull-down experiments, seeing these

436
00:25:17.968 --> 00:25:21.588
transcriptional repression complexes also being recruited to BRD9

437
00:25:21.608 --> 00:25:22.008
loci.

438
00:25:23.288 --> 00:25:26.168
And in fact, this is just the tip of the iceberg of what we've been able to achieve

439
00:25:26.208 --> 00:25:29.788
already. We've now taken other transcription factor targeting ligands,

440
00:25:30.168 --> 00:25:33.998
extended using high-throughput chemistry and direct to biology approaches,

441
00:25:34.448 --> 00:25:37.948
identified a whole bunch of new transcriptional

442
00:25:37.988 --> 00:25:41.888
repressors, transcriptional activators, transcriptional rewiring agents, and

443
00:25:41.928 --> 00:25:45.448
then through pull-down chemoproteomics experiments, identified new transcriptional

444
00:25:45.488 --> 00:25:49.328
epigenetic effector proteins that we can use to manipulate and rewire

445
00:25:49.368 --> 00:25:52.808
transcription in cancer cells in unique ways. All right.

446
00:25:52.868 --> 00:25:55.907
So I'll end there. This is just the tip of the iceberg of what we're working on in

447
00:25:55.928 --> 00:25:59.908
terms of covalent chemoproteomic approaches, and also expanding on targeted

448
00:25:59.918 --> 00:26:03.877
protein degradation platforms. And I think, most compellingly, probably

449
00:26:03.908 --> 00:26:07.108
the most exciting thing that we're working on is this new kind of induced proximity

450
00:26:07.148 --> 00:26:10.018
approaches for manipulating transcriptional pathways,

451
00:26:10.668 --> 00:26:12.968
especially in terms of rewiring them.

452
00:26:13.007 --> 00:26:15.688
And it's just the tip of the iceberg what I showed you.

453
00:26:15.788 --> 00:26:19.438
There are so many molecules we're finding that are uniquely rewiring

454
00:26:19.468 --> 00:26:23.208
transcription in ways that you would not expect by bringing in

455
00:26:23.508 --> 00:26:26.988
neomorphic protein complexes. So hopefully I'll be able to show you more of that

456
00:26:27.248 --> 00:26:30.568
next year. And with that, I'll thank my lab at UC Berkeley.

457
00:26:30.788 --> 00:26:34.648
Many of these projects were also done in collaboration with Novartis and also the

458
00:26:34.708 --> 00:26:37.768
Mark Foundation for Cancer Research, and happy to take questions.

459
00:26:49.578 --> 00:26:52.528
Please use the microphones in the room for questions.

460
00:26:56.668 --> 00:26:56.928
Hi.

461
00:26:58.188 --> 00:26:58.648
Is it on?

