So then to round things out,

1429
01:22:46.706 --> 01:22:50.606
I want to make sure we don't leave without thinking about alternate

1430
01:22:50.686 --> 01:22:54.266
degradation mechanisms beyond the ubiquitin and proteasome system.

1431
01:22:55.466 --> 01:22:59.002
And of course, on the right side of this slideAs you'll know,

1432
01:22:59.262 --> 01:23:02.922
the sort of cellular trash can is the lysosome,

1433
01:23:03.222 --> 01:23:07.142
an organelle that is prevalent in all our cells and actually upregulated in many

1434
01:23:07.182 --> 01:23:10.982
types of cancer. And so we thought about how we

1435
01:23:11.042 --> 01:23:14.922
might leverage this mechanism to degrade other proteins

1436
01:23:14.962 --> 01:23:16.482
like, for example,

1437
01:23:18.182 --> 01:23:21.962
membrane-associated proteins that can be modulated very easily through the

1438
01:23:22.002 --> 01:23:22.621
lysosome.

1439
01:23:23.622 --> 01:23:24.101
And so

1440
01:23:24.922 --> 01:23:28.282
we had a really interesting idea of how to do that,

1441
01:23:28.982 --> 01:23:32.342
because lysosomes actually have a number of

1442
01:23:32.402 --> 01:23:33.082
proteins

1443
01:23:34.882 --> 01:23:38.762
that reside at their membrane and refer to lysosomal membrane

1444
01:23:38.842 --> 01:23:42.622
proteins. And these proteins, some of them can

1445
01:23:42.702 --> 01:23:46.542
be rapidly turned over through a process that is

1446
01:23:46.842 --> 01:23:50.642
ubiquitin and escort machinery-dependent microautophagy,

1447
01:23:51.362 --> 01:23:53.042
such that they're turning over on the

1448
01:23:54.122 --> 01:23:57.922
very rapid timescale. As illustrated here, for one example,

1449
01:23:58.102 --> 01:24:01.042
Rnf152 is a lysosomal membrane protein

1450
01:24:02.302 --> 01:24:04.182
that when you block

1451
01:24:05.382 --> 01:24:08.922
protein synthesis with cycloheximide, as shown in this blot at the bottom left,

1452
01:24:09.942 --> 01:24:13.362
you can see that within four hours, the protein is completely wiped out.

1453
01:24:14.222 --> 01:24:17.242
And so this led to the concept that maybe we could

1454
01:24:17.282 --> 01:24:21.062
piggyback on this constant

1455
01:24:21.072 --> 01:24:24.042
turnover of these proteins by the lysosome

1456
01:24:25.442 --> 01:24:26.872
through these

1457
01:24:28.442 --> 01:24:32.342
lysosomal membrane targeting chimeras or LIMTACS, bifunctional

1458
01:24:32.422 --> 01:24:33.782
molecules that would recruit

1459
01:24:34.642 --> 01:24:38.442
things to the lysosomal membrane that typically aren't there and are dragged

1460
01:24:38.482 --> 01:24:41.982
into the lysosome through this LIMTAC

1461
01:24:42.442 --> 01:24:46.422
mechanism. And so as a proof of concept, we started with

1462
01:24:47.782 --> 01:24:48.562
one of our favorite

1463
01:24:49.362 --> 01:24:52.992
oncogenes, KRAS G12D, to see if we can

1464
01:24:53.022 --> 01:24:56.522
indeed do this. Of course, KRAS is not residing at the

1465
01:24:56.562 --> 01:24:57.562
lysosome typically.

1466
01:24:58.362 --> 01:25:02.122
And so this is illustrated here that indeed this works.

1467
01:25:03.102 --> 01:25:06.172
So you're seeing here in the top row of images,

1468
01:25:07.602 --> 01:25:11.362
you're looking at in the control case, so DMSO treated, you can see

1469
01:25:11.422 --> 01:25:15.231
that on the top left image, KRAS is at the plasma membrane, sort

1470
01:25:15.262 --> 01:25:17.422
of outlining the cell surface.

1471
01:25:18.302 --> 01:25:22.262
Rnf152 overlaps with the lysosomal marker Lamp1.

1472
01:25:22.692 --> 01:25:25.482
It's hanging out at lysosomes, and they're not together.

1473
01:25:26.082 --> 01:25:28.902
However, when you add this tool molecule, this LIMTAC,

1474
01:25:29.642 --> 01:25:32.942
recruits KRAS from the plasma membrane to the

1475
01:25:32.962 --> 01:25:35.942
lysosome membrane through interactions with

1476
01:25:36.142 --> 01:25:37.242
Rnf152.

1477
01:25:38.102 --> 01:25:38.522
And this

1478
01:25:39.422 --> 01:25:43.262
ultimately results in degradation of KRAS

1479
01:25:43.302 --> 01:25:47.182
G12D and inhibition of downstream

1480
01:25:47.242 --> 01:25:50.882
signaling as evidenced through phospho-ERK

1481
01:25:51.322 --> 01:25:51.542
here.

1482
01:25:53.122 --> 01:25:56.702
So we said this is quite interesting. It's a very different type of pharmacology.

1483
01:25:56.742 --> 01:25:58.442
You actually have two things happening.

1484
01:25:59.202 --> 01:26:02.162
You have relocalization. You're changing the

1485
01:26:02.202 --> 01:26:05.842
localization of KRAS from the plasma

1486
01:26:05.902 --> 01:26:09.702
membrane, where it needs to be present to be active to activate

1487
01:26:09.802 --> 01:26:12.581
RAF and downstream MAP kinase signaling.

1488
01:26:13.442 --> 01:26:16.072
You're moving it away from there to the lysosomal membrane,

1489
01:26:16.642 --> 01:26:20.362
and you're turning over the protein at the same time.

1490
01:26:21.022 --> 01:26:24.242
So we thought maybe that pharmacology actually could give you advantage.

1491
01:26:24.702 --> 01:26:26.762
It may lead to more sustained

1492
01:26:27.842 --> 01:26:31.542
inhibition of KRAS signaling even when you wash out the

1493
01:26:31.582 --> 01:26:34.962
molecule. And that's what's shown in this slide here.

1494
01:26:35.722 --> 01:26:37.862
When you use a KRAS inhibitor,

1495
01:26:38.862 --> 01:26:42.532
of course you get rapid, robust inhibition, but when you wash out that molecule,

1496
01:26:43.402 --> 01:26:45.542
phospho-ERK comes back quite quickly.

1497
01:26:45.602 --> 01:26:49.082
However, when we use this LIMTAC mechanism in this third

1498
01:26:50.722 --> 01:26:54.582
column of treatment, you can see sustained degradation of

1499
01:26:54.652 --> 01:26:57.742
KRAS and sustained inhibition of phospho-ERK.

1500
01:26:58.142 --> 01:27:01.982
And this translates into a more robust cell

1501
01:27:02.042 --> 01:27:03.752
killing as evidenced in this

1502
01:27:04.902 --> 01:27:07.582
cell viability assay with the LIMTAC molecule in the red.

1503
01:27:09.462 --> 01:27:10.762
So hopefully

1504
01:27:11.582 --> 01:27:15.322
what you've heard from me today, but more importantly

1505
01:27:16.261 --> 01:27:19.122
from a number of speakers today, is that

1506
01:27:20.582 --> 01:27:23.502
we need continued innovation in drug discovery.

1507
01:27:24.802 --> 01:27:28.482
The low-hanging fruits are gone. We're now only

1508
01:27:28.722 --> 01:27:31.651
reaching high into the tree, and we believe that

1509
01:27:32.142 --> 01:27:36.082
this concept of proximity-based therapeutics

1510
01:27:37.362 --> 01:27:40.802
is really going to be the ladders to get us to those high-hanging fruits.

1511
01:27:41.522 --> 01:27:45.502
And this is allowing us to take on these challenging targets through a

1512
01:27:45.662 --> 01:27:49.442
number of different mechanisms. You've heard about different types of

1513
01:27:49.482 --> 01:27:53.122
degrader modalities that I talked a little bit about and Dan talked about,

1514
01:27:53.582 --> 01:27:54.992
as well as other speakers earlier today.

1515
01:27:55.382 --> 01:27:59.302
But this plethora of new non-degrader mechanisms that you

1516
01:27:59.342 --> 01:28:03.302
heard from Kat and many other speakers throughout the day that just

1517
01:28:04.082 --> 01:28:06.902
allow us to be very creative

1518
01:28:08.902 --> 01:28:11.102
at how we go about doing drug discovery.

1519
01:28:11.151 --> 01:28:14.982
And so I'm very excited to see where the future takes

1520
01:28:15.062 --> 01:28:15.242
us.

1521
01:28:16.862 --> 01:28:20.762
So I'll stop there. Thank many of the people that did the work that are

1522
01:28:20.842 --> 01:28:24.782
listed on this slide. And if there are any questions, I'd

1523
01:28:24.822 --> 01:28:25.662
